  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Blue Petition for the Sovereign's Life Destiny
  author: Kim Geuk-gi
  language: eng
  text: |-
    What can be seen has no form, what can be heard has no sound—truly beyond all measure. Yet dimly there seems an image, suddenly there appears a substance—something we might grasp and lean upon. Consider this humble frame bearing three great responsibilities: I dwell always in thought of difficulty while scheming for ease, yet know not how to discern rightly; I turn my face toward fortune and my back to calamity, yet know not what adornment befits this aim. I ask only to receive good salvation and preserve the long designs of fate.

    On this auspicious day of the sovereign's natal destiny, I examine the subtle prescriptions in the precious canon. The great ritual is splendidly arranged, and with reverent bow I submit to the True Wanderer. The pearl gates and jade palace, though dwelling in depths beyond measure, I envision drawing near on jeweled carriage and jade chariot to this fragrant and flower-blessed assembly.

    Let transgressions fall away like marks from dark paper, let merit be added to the Yellow Register. Cast out calamity, chase away fault. May the anxiety and doubt of precarious circumstance dissolve forever. Guard his life, extend his years—grant that he may at last enjoy the boundless longevity of the turtle age.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: This is a Daoist petition (qingci) composed for a royal birthday celebration, seeking divine blessings through ritual and spiritual intercession.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'Yellow Register' (황록) refers to a celestial record in Daoism; the 'turtle age' (거북 나이) symbolizes extreme longevity and lasting peace.
  - key: ''
    value: The 'True Wanderer' (진유) refers to celestial immortals or deities invoked in Daoist ritual.
